metadata.title: Piper J-3 Cub
aws::graph::propositions: # Piper J-3 Cub Military Service and Variants
Civilian-owned Piper J-3 Cubs joined the war effort as part of the newly formed Civil Air Patrol.
Civil Air Patrol used Piper J-3 Cubs to patrol the Eastern Seaboard.
Civil Air Patrol used Piper J-3 Cubs to patrol the Gulf Coast.
Civil Air Patrol conducted constant searches for German U-boats.
Civil Air Patrol conducted searches for survivors of U-boat attacks.
Piper developed a military variant of the Piper J-3 Cub.
Bill Jr. stated "All we had to do was paint the Cub olive drab to produce a military airplane."
The military variant of the Piper J-3 Cub was designated as the O-59 in 1941.
The military variant of the Piper J-3 Cub was designated as the L-4 after April 1942.
The military variant of the Piper J-3 Cub was designated as the NE by the U.S. Navy.
The L-4 Grasshopper was mechanically identical to the J-3 civilian Cub.
The L-4 Grasshopper was distinguishable by the use of a Plexiglas greenhouse skylight.
The L-4 Grasshopper was distinguishable by the use of rear windows for improved visibility.
The Taylorcraft L-2 also used Plexiglas windows for improved visibility.
The Aeronca L-3 also used Plexiglas windows for improved visibility.
The Taylorcraft L-2 was in use with the US armed forces.
The Aeronca L-3 was in use with the US armed forces.
The L-4 Grasshopper had accommodations for a single passenger in addition to the pilot.

text:
Civilian-owned Cubs joined the war effort as part of the newly formed Civil Air Patrol, patrolling the Eastern Seaboard and Gulf Coast in a constant search for German U-boats and survivors of U-boat attacks.
Piper developed a military variant ("All we had to do," Bill Jr. is quoted as saying, "was paint the Cub olive drab to produce a military airplane"), variously designated as the O-59 (1941), L-4 (after April 1942) and NE (U.S. Navy). The L-4 Grasshopper was mechanically identical to the J-3 civilian Cub, but was distinguishable by the use of a Plexiglas greenhouse skylight and rear windows for improved visibility, much like the Taylorcraft L-2 and Aeronca L-3 also in use with the US armed forces. It had accommodations for a single passenger in addition to the pilot.
